  FINDING: rfx and OpenEMS agree to within 1 % on the TM010
  patch resonance and both land within 2–3 % of the Balanis TL
  analytic value. This is the expected outcome for a well-set-up
  coarse-mesh FDTD crossval on a finite-GP patch antenna.

  Root-cause history (see research note 2026-04-11_crossval12):
   • Before the ground-plane fix, rfx used `pec_faces={"z_lo"}`
     to get a free z-boundary PEC. That turned the entire domain
     floor into an infinite PEC sheet — a cavity, not an antenna —
     and shifted the resonance 8 % high (2.618 vs 2.424 GHz).
   • Before the PML fix, OpenEMS used `MUR` at ≈λ/4 margin which
     reflected energy and made the effective cavity larger,
     shifting the resonance 8 % low (2.231 vs 2.424 GHz).
   • The two bugs pointed in opposite directions and gave a 17 %
     inter-tool gap. With both fixed (rfx = explicit finite PEC box
     BELOW substrate; OpenEMS = PML_8 + 50 mm margin) the gap is
     under 1 %.

  NOTES:
   • Reference tool is OpenEMS (not Meep) because it is the
     canonical open-source patch-antenna reference.
   • rfx single-cell lumped-port S11 dip is shallow (~2 dB) because
     the single-cell port has parasitic reactance — use Harminv for
     the clean resonance frequency, the S11 dip only as a
     passivity / local-dip confirmation.

